<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-124-076 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 889 316</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Reseller News  June 24 1991 n426 p3(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Lotus vows to block Borland: Quattro Pro's legal hurdles. (LotusDevelopment, Borland International)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Darrow, Barbara; Shore, Joel.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Lotus Development plans to seek an injunction against Borland'supcoming Quattro Pro for Windows if it includes a 1-2-3 commandstructure like the one offered in earlier versions.andP;  Should Lotusprevail, distributors, dealers and users will find themselves withillegal products.andP;  Resellers may be able to take advantage of sucha situation because many users are dedicated to Quattro and thelast available copies can be sold at a premium price.andP;  Smartdealers will mark up prices in the face of a shortage.andP;  Microsoft,whose Excel 3.0 spreadsheet includes a 1-2-3 command translationfeature, is likely to be the next target it Lotus wins its suit.andO;Lotus officials have declined comment; Microsoft does not expressconcern.andP;  Lotus filed suit against Borland and The Santa CruzOperation in Jul 1990, right after winning a copyrightinfringement case against Paperback Software.andP;  Two defendants inthe Paperback case were charged with plagiarizing the 1-2-3command menu structure.andP;  Borland has been given until Sep 30, 1991to show cause why the case should be dismissed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Lotus Development Corp. (Cases)Borland International Inc. (Cases).andO;Ticker:    BORL; LOTS.andO;Product:   Lotus 1-2-3 (Spreadsheet software) (Cases)Quattro Pro for Windows (Spreadsheet software) (Cases).andO;Topic:     Law SuitSpreadsheetsCopyrightIntellectual property.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>